Data analysis

First we load the required packages and read the data.

We use the dataset learning2014 (http://www.helsinki.fi/~kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-data.txt), which contains data about a survey of university students and their attitudes towards learning.

The dataset contains 166 observations (students) and 7 variables: age, gender, exam points (points) and summary variables of questions related to deep learning (deep), surface learning (surf), strategic learning (stra) and students’ attitude towards statistics (attitude).

ggpairs(lrn14, mapping = aes(), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))

Next we explore the data using a scatter plot matrix. From the figure we can see the following:

  • The variables seem to be mostly normally distributed. Age is skewed right and points are skewed left
  • There are more women than men in the dataset
  • Males seem to have on average better attitude
  • There is a significant positive correlation between attitude and points
  • There is a milder negative correlation between surface and deep learning (which is to be expected)

We want to make a model from this data where we want to explain the amount of points. We are going to use a linear regression model and choose three explanatory variables. For the first model we are going to choose the demographic variables age and gender and also attitude, which had the highest correlation with points.

model1 <- lm(points ~ age+gender+attitude, data=lrn14)

In order to try to improve the model we replace age and gender with the two variables that had the highest correlation with points besides attitude: stra and surf.

Stra and surf were neither associated with points, thus we are left with a model with only attitude as the explaining variable:

model3 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data=lrn14)
summary(model3)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = lrn14)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

In this model attitude is highly significantly associated with points (p=4.12e-09). The estimate for attitude is 3.5 meaning that for every one point increase in attitude the points will increase by 3.5. The intercept is 11.6, meaning that if the attitude is 0 the points will be 11.6. For this model the R-squared is 0.19 meaning that this model explains about 19% of the variance in points.

To analyse whether the assumptions of linear regression are met, we are going to draw the diagnostic plots: Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage.

par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model3, which=c(1,2,5))

The main assumptions of linear regression are

  • Linear relationship between predictors and outcome
  • The residuals are independent of each other
  • The variance of residuals is equal and does not depend on the value of the response variable
  • The residuals are normally distributed

The linear relationship between attitude and points can be seen from the previous scatter plot. From the residuals vs. fitted plot we can see that residuals are evenly spaced throughout the fitted values, meaning that the assumption of equal variance of residuals is met and they seem to be independent of each other. From the Q-Q plot we can see that the residuals follow quite well a straight line (except for some differences in the extremes), meaning that the assumption of normality of the residuals is met. Finally, from the residuals vs. leverage plot we can see that none of the points is close to the Cook’s distance, meaning that there are no outliers which would influence the model too strongly.

The dataset in question is called “Student Performance Data Set” and describes student achievement in secondary education of two Portuguese schools. The data attributes include student grades, demographic, social and school related features and it was collected by using school reports and questionnaires. We are especially interested in the student’s alcohol consumption. Alc_use tells about the alcohol use using a scale from 1 to 5 (5 is highest use). High alcohol use (high_use variable) is defined as alcohol use >2.

We are going to study which factors predict high alcohol use in students. I have chosen the following four variables, which might explain the alcohol consumption:

  • Failures (number of past class failures). My hypothesis is that those who have more class failures are more likely to be those that have high alcohol use
  • Absences (number of school absences). My hypothesis is that those who have more school absences are more likely to be those that have high alcohol use
  • Sex. My hypothesis is that males drink more alcohol (based on population data)
  • Age. My hypothesis is that older students drink more alcohol

Next we are going to explore the distributions of the above mentioned variables and their relationships with alcohol consumption

#Failures
alc %>% ggplot(aes(failures, fill=high_use)) + geom_bar()

#Absences
alc %>% ggplot(aes(absences, fill=high_use)) + geom_bar()

#Sex
alc %>% ggplot(aes(sex, fill=high_use)) + geom_bar()

table(alc$sex, alc$high_use)
##    
##     FALSE TRUE
##   F   154   41
##   M   105   70
#Age
alc %>% ggplot(aes(high_use, age)) + geom_boxplot()

  • Failures: Most students have 0 failures. There seems to be a significantly larger proportion of students with high alcohol use among those with 1+ failures.
  • Absences: Most students have just a few absences, but a larger proportion of those who have many absences seem to also have high alcohol use
  • Sex: There are more females than males in the dataset, but the difference is small. It looks that a larger proportion of males have high alcohol use compared to females
  • Age: It looks that those who have high alcohol use are older than those with low alcohol use

Next we are going to make a logistic regression model to predict high alcohol use. We are going to use the above mentioned variables as the explanatory variables

model <- glm(high_use ~ failures+absences+sex+age, family="binomial", data=alc)
summary(model)

From the model summary we can see that failures, absences and sex are significantly associated with high alcohol use in this model (p<0.05) while age is not (p>0.05). By using the exp function we can get the odds ratios from the model coefficients, which are log odds. From the error terms we can compute the confidence intervals.

  • Failures: Every failure increases the odds of high alcohol use by 1.78 (95% CI 1.17-2.69)
  • Absences: Every absence increases the odds of high alcohol use by 1.09 (1.05-1.15)
  • Sex: Male sex increases the odds of high alcohol use by 2.72 (1.68-4.45)
  • Age: One year increase in age increases the odds of high alcohol use by 1.11 (0.91-1.37), which is not a significant result because the confidence interval includes the value 1

My hypotheses were correct except for the association of age, which was not significant in this model.

We are going to make a final model using only the predictors that were significant (failures, absences, sex).

Next we are going to explore the predictive power of our model.

probabilities <- predict(finalmodel, type = "response")
# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability>0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   252    7
##    TRUE     78   33
# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2297297

We can calculate that about 23% of the predictions were incorrect. I think this is a quite good result. By simple guessing or coin flipping we would get about 50% of the predictions correct, so the model is a good improvement.

The Boston data set contains information about housing values in suburbs of Boston. It contains data about 506 suburbs (rows) and 14 variables, for example crime rate, distance to employment centers and accessibility to highways. More information can be found at https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/MASS/html/Boston.html.

#Create a categorical variable of the crime rate
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = quantile(boston_scaled$crim), include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high" ))

# add the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

#Divide the dataset to train and test sets, so that 80% of the data belongs to the train set
ind <- sample(nrow(boston_scaled),  size = nrow(boston_scaled) * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

Next we will fit the linear discriminant analysis on the train set using the categorical crime rate as the target variable and all the other variables in the data set as predictor variables

lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

#Draw the LDA (bi)plot
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Now we will predict the classes with the LDA model on the test data and examine the results.

#Save the crime categories from the test set and then remove the categorical crime variable from the test dataset. 
correct_classes <- test$crime
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

#Predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

#Cross tabulate the results
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       15      11        0    0
##   med_low    4      12        5    0
##   med_high   0      14       18    1
##   high       0       0        0   22

Our model classifies the suburbs with high crime category with 100% accuracy. Medium high and low categories are also classified with quite good accuracy. However, the medium low category is more spread out and the model seems to struggle with it.

pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)

By plotting the number of clusters vs. WCSS we can see that the greatest drop happens when the number of clusters is 2, so that seems to be the optimal number of clusters.

From the pair plot we can see that the variables which seem to most affect the clustering are zn, indus, rad and tax.

The human dataset describes countries and their human development index and related properties, such as life expectancy, education and gender equality.

The variables are the following:

  • “GNI” = Gross National Income per capita. GNI is heavily right skewed. It is significantly negatively correlated with Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth and positively correlated with Life.Exp, Edu.Exp and Edu2.FM
  • “Life.Exp” = Life expectancy at birth. It is left skewed and correlates negatively with Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth and positively with GNI, Edu2.FM, Edu.Exp
  • “Edu.Exp” = Expected years of schooling. It seems to be near to a normal distribution. It is positively correlated with Edu2.FM, Life.Exp and GNI and negatively correlated with Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth
  • “Mat.Mor” = Maternal mortality ratio is heavily left skewed and positively correlated with Ado.Birth and negatively with Edu2.FM, Edu.Exp, Life.Exp and GNI
  • “Ado.Birth” = Adolescent birth rate is left skewed. It is correlated positively with Mat.Mor and negatively with Edu2.FM, Edu.Exp, Life.Exp and GNI
  • “Edu2.FM” = Ratio of proportion of females with at least secondary education to proportion of males with at least secondary education. It has some left tail, but otherwise quite symmetrical. It is positively correlated with Edu.Exp, Life.Exp and GNI and negatively with Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth
  • “Labo.FM” = Ratio of proportion of females in the labour force to proportion of males in the labour force. It is right skewed. It has no strong correlations
  • “Parli.F” = Percetange of female representatives in parliament. It is a bit left skewed. It also has no strong correlations

Now when using the standardized variables the results are spread out nicely and we can interpret them. In this analysis the first two components explain 54% and 16% (70% together) of the variability. The first component is affected positively by maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate and negatively by expected years of schooling, life expectancy, GNI and female education. Thus PC1 seems to reflect the general level of development of the countries (eg. things associated with a developing country vs. developed country). PC2 is affected mainly by the percentage of female representatives in the parliament and the amount of females in the labor force. Thus PC2 represents the station and participation of females in the society.

Looks like the Dim 1 is related mainly to the place where the tea is bought from, eg. tea shop vs. chain store and also whether it is in tea bags or unpackaged. It is obvious that when purchasing tea from a tea shop the tea is not in tea bags.

Dim 2 seems to be more related to the taste in tea, eg. type of tea and what is used with the tea.
